Item 66. In addition to any other funds appropriated by the provisions of this act,
there is appropriated the sum of $750,000 (nonrecurring) to the Department of Finance
and Administration for the sole purpose of making a grant in such amount to Hope
- 33 - 011112

House, to be used for programs and services for pregnant teens and teenage mothers in
the City of Cookeville.
Item 67. In addition to any other funds appropriated by the provisions of this act,
there is appropriated the sum of $518,600 (recurring) to the Attorney General and
Reporter for the sole purpose of restoring the base reduction to salary equity funds, as
identified on Page A-29 of the 2026-2027 Budget Document.
Item 68. In addition to any other funds appropriated by the provisions of this act,
there is appropriated the sum of $3,702,300 (recurring) to the Department of Finance
and Administration for the sole purpose of providing funds for salary pool and
operational costs for higher education institution nonformula units.
Item 69. In addition to any other funds appropriated by the provisions of this act,
there is appropriated the sum of $4,000,000 (nonrecurring) to the Department of
Transportation for the sole purpose of widening State Route 99 (Salem Highway) for
approximately 2.5 miles in the Rockvale Community of Rutherford County.
Item 70. In addition to any other funds appropriated by the provisions of this act,
there is appropriated the sum of $3,500,000 (nonrecurring) to the Tennessee Higher
Education Commission for the sole purpose of making a grant for the TN Achieves
program.
Item 71. In addition to any other funds appropriated by the provisions of this act,
there is appropriated the sum of $1,200,000 (nonrecurring) to the Department of Finance
and Administration for the sole purpose of making a grant in such amount to Junior
Achievement of East Tennessee, Inc., to be used for a pilot project focused on the
statewide implementation of the Junior Achievement (JA) Financial Literacy Semester
Course—an evidence-based, standards-aligned solution that ensures Tennessee high
school graduates are financially capable, career-ready, and prepared for long-term
economic success.
- 34 - 011112

Item 72. In addition to any other funds appropriated by the provisions of this act,
there is appropriated the sum of $100,000 (nonrecurring) to the Department of Finance
and Administration for the sole purpose of making a grant in such amount to the City of
Harriman, to be used for infrastructure and economic development off State Highway 29
(Pine Ridge Road) north of Interstate 40, Exit 350, including planning and design for
such development.
Item 73. In addition to any other funds appropriated by the provisions of this act,
there is appropriated the sum of $70,000 (nonrecurring) to the Commission on Children
and Youth for the sole purpose of expanding Court Appointed Special Advocates
(CASA) programs to three (3) additional counties.
Item 74. In addition to any other funds appropriated by the provisions of this act,
there is appropriated the sum of $20,000 (nonrecurring) to the Department of Finance
and Administration for the sole purpose of making a grant in such amount to the
municipal government of the City of Elizabethton, to be used for the reconstruction and
refurbishing of the Hampton Community Water Tower.
Item 75. In addition to any other funds appropriated by the provisions of this act,
there is appropriated the sum of $30,000 (nonrecurring) to the Department of Finance
and Administration for the sole purpose of making a grant in such amount to the county
government of Johnson County, to be used for the planning and engineering of the Multi
Sports Complex for the youth of Johnson County.
Item 76. In addition to any other funds appropriated by the provisions of this act,
there is appropriated the sum of $7,000,000 (nonrecurring) to the Department of Human
Services to be used exclusively for the Summer Electronic Benefits Transfer (EBT)
Program.
REPORTS
AND FURTHER AMEND by adding the following new items in Section 23:
- 35 - 011112

Item __. All intra-agency transfers within organizational units of state
government shall be reported by the Department of Finance and Administration to the
Directors of the Office of Legislative Budget Analysis on a quarterly basis.
Item __. It is the intent of the General Assembly that any new or expanded
program or system that uses vendors and is funded through the Rural Healthcare
Transformation Program must be procured, to the extent permitted under federal law,
through a competitive bidding process when the use of such a process will not
jeopardize federal funding. Beginning July 1, 2026, the Department of Health shall
submit a monthly report to the Chairs of the Finance, Ways and Means Committees of
the Senate and the House of Representatives and the Office of Legislative Budget
Analysis detailing the following information concerning the Rural Health Transportation
("RHT") Program:
(a) Each RHT-funded program or system procured during the prior
month;
(b) Whether such program or system was competitively bid;
(c) If not competitively bid, then an explanation of why a noncompetitive
procurement method was used;
(d) Any new vendors selected for each program or system;
(e) Whether the selected vendor was the lowest-cost bidder and the
number of bidders for each competitively bid procurement;
(f) The total cost of each program or system;
(g) The estimated number of state employees that would be required to
continue each program or system upon the expiration of federal funding; and
(h) The estimated annual amount of state funding required to continue
each program or system once federal funding is fully expended.
LOCAL COSTS OVER $1M
AND FURTHER AMEND by inserting the following new item in Section 42:
- 36 - 011112

Item __. In addition to any other funds appropriated by the provisions of this act,
there is hereby appropriated a sum sufficient to cities and counties for the sole purpose
of funding the state share of the mandated local cost of implementing the provisions of
Senate Bill 225 / House Bill 29, relative to changing the payment methodology for
services rendered by a chiropractic physician to be the same as a medical physician, if
such bill becomes a law. The state share shall be an amount equal to ten percent (10%)
of the mandated local cost of implementing such bill.
HOUSE KEEPING – TYPOGRAPHICAL CORRECTIONS
AND FURTHER AMEND by requesting the Engrossing Clerk to:
(1) Delete the bold underlined explanatory headings in this amendment; and
(2) Exclude this paragraph from the engrossed bill.
